# collab.conf.example — copy to collab/collab.conf.local (git-ignored) to set your
# persistent ClaudeCollab preferences, or run /collab:configure, which writes it
# for you. Simple KEY=value lines; `#` starts a comment; this file is NOT executed.
#
# Why a file and not environment variables: this tool is driven by Claude Code, whose
# shell runs each command in a subshell — so a setup command can't `export` a value
# into your interactive shell and have it persist. A git-ignored file can. The env
# vars still work as one-off overrides (precedence: -m flag / args > env > this file).
#
# Values here are read by collab/ask.sh (COLLAB_MODEL) and collab/panel-models.sh
# (COLLAB_MODELS). Model policy (deny/ask/allow) lives separately in
# $COLLAB_POLICY when set, otherwise a ruleful collab/models.policy.local,
# otherwise committed collab/models.policy. See /collab:configure.

# Default model for /collab:consult (and any single-model call). Prefer a NON-Claude model
# so a second opinion is genuinely independent.
# COLLAB_MODEL=openai/gpt-5

# Default panel for /collab:panel: 2-3 ordered ids from DIFFERENT providers (space- or
# comma-separated). panel-models.sh warns if the set isn't cross-provider.
# COLLAB_MODELS=openai/gpt-5 google/gemini-2.5-pro

# Where collab/ask.sh looks for the collab-* agent DEFS when deciding whether to fall
# back to a weaker built-in agent. Default: the sibling .opencode/agent of the install.
# Set this only for a non-sibling layout (e.g. a shared/global install whose agent defs
# live in opencode's global config dir). NOTE: this governs ONLY the wrapper's fallback
# decision — opencode resolves --agent independently from its own config, so this MUST
# point at the SAME directory the defs were actually installed to, or the wrapper's
# "def present" check and opencode's resolution disagree.
# COLLAB_AGENT_DIR=~/.config/opencode/agent

# --- Evidence layer (collab/log.sh) ---------------------------------------------
# Every model call is recorded to the git-ignored collab/logs/<run_id>/calls.jsonl:
# raw prompts and responses, with `expected-call`, `started`, and `completed`
# lifecycle entries sharing one call_id. This is what a watcher agent
# audits INSTEAD of Claude's own summary of the exchange — so it is on by default.
# COLLAB_LOG=off                  # stop recording entirely (nothing to audit)
# COLLAB_LOG_PROMPTS=full         # full | hash | off — what to keep of the prompt
#                                 # Claude SENT. Default `full`: the brief Claude
#                                 # wrote is itself prime audit material. But it
#                                 # means the log holds whatever repo context was
#                                 # pasted in — use `hash` (digest only, proves the
#                                 # prompt didn't change) or `off` on sensitive work.
#                                 # Responses are ALWAYS kept in full: they are the
#                                 # evidence, and they're the other model's words.
# COLLAB_LOG_RETENTION_DAYS=14    # prune runs older than this; 0 disables pruning
# COLLAB_LOG_PARTITION=1          # opt-in (default OFF). Narrow the log root to a
#                                 # per-project subdir BELOW the base logs tree:
#                                 # <base>/<project-key>/<run>, keyed by the CWD's git
#                                 # top-level (else the CWD). Keeps each project's runs,
#                                 # `latest` symlink, retention, and /collab:witness
#                                 # resolution separate under a single shared install.
#                                 # DISABLED when COLLAB_LOG_DIR is explicitly set (an
#                                 # explicit dir wins). The subdir stays under
#                                 # collab/logs/, so --watch's scope still matches.
#                                 # For a NON-repo project the key uses $PWD (logical),
#                                 # so entering the same dir via different symlink paths
#                                 # yields two buckets (split logs / stale `latest`) —
#                                 # bounded, not corruption.

# Model the watcher (/collab:witness) uses to audit whether Claude's account of a model
# exchange matched what the models actually said. Falls back to COLLAB_MODEL if unset.
# It MUST NOT be a Claude model — Claude is the party under audit, so ask.sh refuses
# one (exit 8) unless you explicitly confirm.
# COLLAB_WATCH_MODEL=openai/gpt-5.5

# /collab:witness accepts the default collab/logs root or a child beneath it.
# `collab/ask.sh --watch` mechanically rejects an effective COLLAB_LOG_DIR outside
# that tree before calling a model; arbitrary custom roots still work for logging.
